title: For Sale:  Antique Japanese Samurai Sword
postcontent:
Bought this sword from a live estate auction in Youngstown a few months ago. I have been checking and had a local antiques dealer look at it. He had a student that is Japanese look at it and try to read the papers with the sword.

The antiques dealer took the handle off to see who made the sword. The handle was very rusty, it does have the makers writing on the handle but he could not be read it due to the rust.

It is a long sword called katana from the hand guard to the top of the sword is 28 ½” long.
There are grooves in the sword on both sides and is very sharp.

The temper line is rolling and you can see swirls in the metal. The student said that is from pounding the steel to make the sword.

The handle is a military handle with a Captain officer identification cord and the ends of the handle where the cord is tied is silver.

The hand guard is old steel with waves and gold dots.

The sheath looks newer but very nice with stripes but had a leather cover on it but the cover was very dry and fell apart after the dealer took it off the sheath and carrying it around.

There was an envelope on the sheath that has Japanese documents in them and I was told they are the license and a note that says something about 1680.

I have checked Ebay and seen similar swords selling for $3500 to $10000 dollars. The antique dealer said I should get at least $3500 and maybe more. He is willing to put it in his auction in a couple months but I want to try and sell it now for extra Christmas money.  THE ONLY WAY I WILL SELL IS FOR CASH FACE TO FACE OR USING PAYPAL IF THE BUYER PAYS THE PAYPAL FEES AND SHIPPING.

Essentially the factories saved money by not employing skilled milling craftsmen that were required to produce milled parts.

Regardless of which rifle you choose, you will have a very good rifle that will last you forever!
